metadata.description: OSM tag standards fetched from TagInfo API

amenity.description: A place for parking cars.
A single parking space on a parking lot.
A place for people to sit, allowing room for one or more people.
A restaurant sells full sit-down meals with servers, and may sell alcohol.
A place where religious services are conducted.
A primary or secondary school (pupils typically aged 6 to 18).
A single small container for depositing garbage that is easily accessible for pedestrians.
A parking space designed for bicycles.
A place concentrating on very fast counter-only service and take-away food.
A generally informal place with sit-down facilities selling beverages and light meals and/or snacks.
A small structure for protection against bad weather conditions
A retail facility for refueling motor vehicles
A container or centre that accepts waste material for reuse or recycling.
Indicates publicly accessible toilets.
A shop where a pharmacist sells medications.
A financial establishment where customers can, among other services, deposit money and take loans.
A box to deposit outgoing postal items.
A drinking water source which provides potable water for consumption.
A place for looking after preschool children and (typically) giving early education.
A vending machine sells food, drinks, tickets or other goods automatically.
An open or enclosed platform used by hunters to place themselves at an elevated height above the terrain.
A medium or large disposal bin, typically for bagged up household or industrial waste.

An establishment that sells alcoholic drinks to be consumed on the premises, characterised by a noisy and vibrant atmosphere. They usually do not sell food to be eaten as a meal. The music is usually loud and you often have to stand.
A entrance to an underground or multi storey parking facility
A device that provides the clients of a financial institution with access to financial transactions.
A hospital providing in-patient medical treatment.
A place where letters and parcels may be sent or collected.
A clinic is a medical centre, with more staff than a doctor's office, that does not admit inpatients.
A place mostly used for local events, festivities and group activities.

An establishment that sells alcoholic drinks that can be consumed on the premises, characterised by a traditional appearance and a relaxed atmosphere. Also sells food which also can be eaten on the premises. Customers can usually sit down at a table.
A doctor's office, a place to get medical attention or a check up from a physician.
A fountain with cultural, decorational or historical significance or which serves a recreational purpose.
A townhall serves as a community administrative center or meeting place.
A place where people (or sometimes animals) are buried, usually close to a place of worship.
A facility that provides social services.
A location where electric vehicles can be charged.
A police station is a facility where police officers patrol from and that is a first point of contact for civilians.
A dentist practice / surgery.
A station from which a fire brigade operates.
A facility used to clean the exterior of motor vehicles
A place to read and/or borrow books.
A marketplace where goods and services are traded daily or weekly.
A place, often unattended, where you can pick up and drop off rented bikes.
A public telephone.
A place where children are looked after which is not an tag:amenity=kindergarten.
Machine for picking up and sending parcels.
A place for further education, a post-secondary education institution which is not a University
A bus station would usually be a terminus where many routes stop / start, and where you can change between routes, etc.
A place that deals with the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of disease in animals.
A place that sells ice cream and/or frozen yoghurt over the counter.
An educational institution designed for instruction, examination, or both, of students in many branches of advanced learning.
A place where live performances occur, such as plays, musicals and formal concerts.
A place where taxis wait for passengers. Often near where many people congregate.
A permanently built place for having a BBQ.
A place which is designated for parking motorcycles.
A place where you can get large amounts of drinking water for refilling fresh water holding tanks.
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:building=public or tag:building=civic or a feature tag like tag:office=government, tag:amenity=townhall instead.
A street furniture containing books. Take one, leave one.
A place where people, cars etc. can board and leave a ferry.
A container that holds sand, salt and gravel to spread on roads for winter safety.
A school to learn to drive a motor vehicle.
Private mailboxes where mailmen or other people deposit letters to specific addresses.
Public showers, where people can bathe under water sprays
A loading dock is an entrance to a building used for loading and unloading goods vehicles.
A movie theater, a place showing movies.
A publicly visible clock
A building which is home to a court of law, which administers justice according to the rule of law.
A place from which cars can be rented.
A place that provides facilities for events such as banquets, weddings etc.
An arts centre. A venue where a variety of arts are performed or conducted
A place where water is contained and animals such as horses can drink.
A place to dance and drink at night. Also known as a disco.
An office that exchanges foreign currency and travellers cheques.
A public tool for self-repair of bicycles.
A trolley bay (aka cart corral) is the place where trolleys are "parked".
A studio used for creating radio or television programmes and broadcasting them. It can also be used to mark a music recording studio.
A place with sit-down facilities shared by multiple self-service food vendors.
An active monastery or convent, occupied by a community of monks or nuns living under religious vows.
A place whose principal role is providing internet services.
A prison or jail where people are incarcerated before trial or after conviction
Self-service payment kiosk/terminal.
A centre of fraternities, sororities, professional societies, union halls and other nonprofit organization.
A home for disabled/elderly persons who need permanent care.
A facility for communal bathing that is open to the public.
An object for people to lie down.
A facility where animals are bred, usually to sell them.
Music school, an educational institution specialized in the study, training, and research of music
A place where legally-required vehicle inspection may be performed
An analog device which validates public transport tickets, or devices which are integrated in systems to gain access to an area or service like public transport or parking garages.
Carsharing station, where you get your booked car, often separate areas on parking places.
A device to inflate tyres, mostly of motor vehicles.
A place where mobile money can be payed in and out.
A public place where people come to wash their clothes manually
A large weight scale to weigh vehicles and goods.
An open-air seating area where beer is served.
Tutor or test prep centre.
Place for depositing human waste from a toilet holding tank.
An educational institution where one studies a foreign language.
A formal training place for any of the Japanese do arts.

shop.description: A small local shop carrying a variety of everyday products, such as packaged food and hygiene products.
A large shop selling groceries, fresh produce, and other goods.
A shop which primarily sells clothing
A hairdressers or barbers shop, where hair is cut
A business where cars are repaired.
A shop selling bread
A shop of unspecified type or an indicator that a feature such as a fuel station has a shop.
A non-hairdresser beauty shop, spa, nail salon, etc.
A place that primarily sells cars (automobiles)
Shop selling primarily metal fasteners and tools, sometimes also other workshop and homeware products.
A shop that primarily sells mobile phones and accessories.
A small shop on the pavement that sells magazines, tobacco, newspapers, sweets and stamps.
A shop selling meat or meat products.
A shop selling furniture.
A place selling auto parts, auto accessories, motor oil, car chemicals, etc.
A shop selling alcoholic drinks
A shop selling bouquets of flowers.
A variety store or price-point retailer is a retail shop that sells inexpensive items.
A shop selling consumer electronics such as TVs, radios and fridges.
A shop selling shoes
A shop that sells, fits, and repairs prescription eyeglasses and contact lenses.
A shop that sells rings, necklaces, earrings, watches, etc.
A group of stores, typically associated with a single building structure.
Shop primarily used to pick-up items ordered online. May have meager supply of products.
Shop selling gifts, greeting cards, or tourist gifts (souvenirs).
A Do-it-Yourself-store, a large hardware and home improvement shop
A shop which sells fruits and vegetables
Shop that is currently not being used.
A shop selling articles of personal hygiene, cosmetics, and household cleaning products.
A store specializing in the sale of books, although it may also sell other printed publications, such as newspapers and magazines.
A store where you can buy and/or repair your bike and buy accessories.
A large store with multiple clothing and other general merchandise departments.
A shop to wash clothes and bedding, generally self-service and unattended.
A shop selling travel related products and services
A shop selling office supplies.
A shop selling pets and/or pet supplies
A shop selling sports equipment and clothing.
A shop selling sweets and candies.
A shop selling tyres.
Shop primarily selling cosmetics.
A shop selling computers, peripherals, software, ...
A shop selling tobacco, and possibly other convenience items
A place where clothing is made, repaired, or altered professionally, especially suits and men's clothing.
Paid storage of household goods, i.e. self storage.
A place of business that sells to a particular trade or trades, but normally also retails to normal consumers.
A shop or kiosk offering a clothes dry cleaning service.
A shop that offers photocopying and printing services.
A shop that sells motorcycles and/or related accessories and services.
A shop that provides services related to funeral arrangements, may also be known as a "funeral parlour" or "undertakers".
Massage shop
Shop focused on selling beverages and drinks, possibly including alcoholic and non-alcoholic ones.
A shop selling newspapers and magazines.
A shop selling potted plants, seedlings for planting, and related items.
A shop at a farm, selling farm produce.
A shop where sweet bakery products are sold.
A shop selling tickets for concerts, events, public transport, etc.
Shop focused on selling interior decorations
A shop selling food.
A general store. Small shop selling variety of different products.
A delicatessen store
A shop focussed on selling children's toys.
A shop selling small household items
A shop selling fish/seafood.
Shop selling bottled wine.
A place where people can get permanent tattoos
A shop where you can buy paints.
A business that offers secured loans against items of personal property as collateral.
A store that sells items in bulk.
A shop selling second hand goods.
A shop dealing with photos or video in any way.
A shop operated by a charity
A store where you can buy medical equipment for private persons.
A shop that takes bets on sporting and other events at agreed upon odds.
A shop that specialises in selling mattresses and other bedding products.
A shop which sells works of art.
A shop where you can plan and buy your kitchen.
A shop selling trekking, climbing, camping equipment.
A shop that sells fabric
A shop of which the main or only purpose is the sale of lottery tickets.
A shop where you can buy antiques.
Shop selling products for agricultural use, such as pesticides, seeds, animal feed, etc.
A shop selling primarily packaged coffee.
A shop selling electronic cigarettes.
A shop selling and/or refilling bottled gas.
A shop selling perfumes.
A place where customers can buy supplies for making art and crafts.
A shop specialized in selling hearing aids devices.
Shop for white goods.
A shop offering small personal loans at high rates of interest.
Shop selling electrical supplies and devices.
A shop selling tea, mostly loose-leaf, by weight.
A place where you can get your motorcycles repaired.
A shop selling bags.
A shop where you can buy objects for babies, like clothes, prams, cots or baby's baths.
A small shop that sells expensive or designer clothing and/or accessories. Often misused due to its use in many different contexts.
A shop selling dairy products.
Shop selling musical instruments, lyrics, scores.
A shop offering grooming services for pets (most frequently dogs)
A store that primarily sells recorded music (typically vinyl/CDs).
A shop selling carpets.

tourism.description: Information for tourists and visitors, including information offices
Hotel – an establishment that provides paid lodging.
A public piece of art.
An object of interest for a tourist, or a purpose-built tourist attraction
A place worth visiting, often high, with a good view of surrounding countryside or notable buildings.
Accommodation smaller than a hotel and typically owner-operated, such as bed&breakfasts etc.
A locality that is suitable for outdoors eating, with facilities to aid a picnic such as tables and benches.
An area where people can camp overnight using tents, camper vans, or caravans.
A tent or caravan pitch location within a campsite or caravan site.
A museum: an institution with exhibitions on scientific, historical, cultural topics
A holiday cottage with self-contained cooking and bathroom facilities.
A furnished apartment or flat with cooking and bathroom facilities that can be rented for holiday vacations.
Cheap accommodation with shared bedrooms.
Short term accommodation, particularly for people travelling by car.
A place where you can stay in a caravan overnight or for longer periods.
An area or building that displays a variety of visual art exhibitions.
A remote building, typically unserviced, providing temporary shelter and sleeping accommodation.
A remote building located in the mountains intended to provide board and lodging.
An amusement park where entertainment is provided by rides, games, concessions.
A general tourist attraction.
A zoological garden, where animals are confined for viewing by the public.
A facility with living aquatic animals for public viewing.
Trail riding station.
A wine cellar, a storage room for wine in bottles or barrels.
Small country property specifically used for organising hunting parties
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:leisure=resort or tag:leisure=beach_resort or tag:tourism=hotel instead.
An establishment offering relaxing treatment for health and beauty, the types that are called spa-treatments. Should involve some kind of bathing.
Type of guided tours offered for tourists and visitors.

highway.description: Road in a residential area
Provides access to a building, service station, beach, campsite, industrial estate, business park, etc.
A minor land-access road like a farm or forest track.
A path mainly or exclusively for pedestrians.
Public access road, non-residential.
A generic path used by pedestrians, small vehicles, for animal riding or livestock walking. Not designated for use by two-track vehicles. Very broad, non-specific meaning.
The location of a street crossing for pedestrians, cyclists, or equestrians.
A road linking small settlements, or the local centres of a large town or city.
A highway linking large towns. In cities, an arterial road of lesser importance.
A single pole with one or more lights to illuminate the street.
A bus stop is a place where public buses stop for passengers.
A highway linking large towns. In cities, a major arterial road.
A widened area of road that allows vehicles to turn more easily.
Road with very low speed limits and other pedestrian friendly traffic rules.
A point at which a vehicle must come to a complete stop.
For designated cycleways.
For flights of steps on footways and paths.
A traffic signal (or a set of those) for regulating circulation.
An important road that is not a motorway.
Used to mark give way (also known as yield) signs or markings.
High capacity highways designed to safely carry fast motor traffic.
The link roads (sliproads / ramps) leading to and from a motorway.
Roads mainly / exclusively for pedestrians
The link road (sliproad / ramp) leading to and from a trunk highway.
Connecting slip roads/ramps of primary highways
A highway (road, track or path) currently under construction.
Connecting slip roads/ramps of secondary highways
Connecting slip road/ramp of a tertiary highway.
An exit from a motorway or other major road.
Stone or metal marker on the side of a road indicating a reference and an approximation of the distance travelled.
A platform at a bus stop or station.
A widened area of a highway with a non-traversable island for turning around, often circular and at the end of a road.
A road that is about to be built, but where any construction work hasn't yet been started.
A way intended for use by equestrians.
A fixed road-side or overhead speed camera.
A corridor inside a building
A passing place on a single track road.
A road junction where the traffic goes around a painted circle or traversable island and has right of way.
Sign number which can be used to define your current position in case of an emergency.
An elevator (or lift) is used to travel vertically, providing passenger and freight access between pathways at different floor levels. May be solely vertical (typical case) or inclined.
Road with unknown classification.
A racetrack for motorised racing, e.g. cars, motorbikes and karts.
Place where drivers can leave the road to rest, but not refuel.
Mirror that reflects the traffic on one road when direct view is blocked.
A dedicated, separate roadway for buses.
Place where drivers can leave a road to refuel, rest, or take refreshments.
An area beside a highway where you can safely stop your car in case of breakdown or emergency.
A trailhead is a designated or customary place where a trip on a trail begins or ends.
A tag on a node to denote a transponder or camera gantry that exists for the purpose of electronically collecting tolls.
Identifies an intersection at which one road has the right of way (priority) while another road must stop or give way.
A mountain route equipped with fixed cables, stemples, ladders, and bridges where climber is attached to supporting equipment limiting fall.
A dynamic electronic sign that displays the speed of the passer-by motorist
Traffic sign object at its actual location.
Sometimes used to show that a way is not a (physical) highway on objects where it would not be obvious otherwise.
Emergency lane beside long descending slopes for trucks to stop after brake failure.
Use for a ladder, a vertical or inclined set of steps or rungs intended for climbing or descending of a person with the help of hands.
Street furniture and devices for cyclists that are intended to make waiting at esp. traffic lights more comfortable.
A busway that is side guided "rails like", not suitable for other traffic.
An official hitchhiking spot.
Do not use, use tag:highway=road instead.
Piste segments that do not exist without snow.
A chemin de ronde was devised as a walkway allowing guards and defenders to patrol the tops of ramparts, protected from the outside by the battlements or a parapet.

building.description: A building of an unspecified type.
A single dwelling unit usually inhabited by one family.
A general tag for a building constructed primarily for residential purposes.
A detached house: a free-standing residential building usually housing a single family.
Denotes a single-owner private garage
A building arranged into individual dwellings, often on separate floors. May also have retail outlets on the ground floor.
A small, simple structure used as storage or workshop
A building constructed to house some manufacturing process
A small and crude shelter.
A building on a farm that is not a dwelling.
A building open on at least two sides.
A house that shares a common wall with another on one side.
The outline of a linear row of residential dwellings, each of which normally has its own entrance, which form a terrace ("row-house" or "townhouse" in North American English).
A building constructed for non-specific commercial activities to take place there.
A generic school building.
A building primarily used for selling goods to the public.
A building under construction
A less important building near to and on the same piece of land as a larger building.
A block of private garages each with a separate owner.
An agricultural building that can be used for storage and as a covered workplace.
A building in which plants are grown
A small, roughly built house typically found in rural areas.
Service building usually is a small unmanned building with certain machinery (like pumps or transformers).
A mobile home (caravan) (semi)permanently left on a single site.
A commercial building for storage of goods.
A building that was built as a church.
Simple single-storey flat house.
A farmhouse is the main building of a farm
A small outbuilding for short visits in a allotment garden.
A carport is a covered structure used to offer limited protection to vehicles, primarily cars, from the elements.
A building which contains spaces mainly designed to be used for offices.
Frequently used to mark ruined buildings. However, this usage conflicts with general use of building tag. In theory it should only be used for buildings constructed to look like ruins.
A building hosting any civic amenity (town hall, library, swimming pool).
A building constructed as accessible to the public (town hall, police station, court house).
A university building.
A building which forms part of a hospital.
A building designed with separate rooms available for overnight accommodation.
A generic kindergarten building.
A building for storing boats
Building built as chapel.
A building that was built as a mosque.
A building constructed to house some manufacturing process, see also tag:building=industrial.
A storage tank
A portable, round tent (yurt or ger)
A building used for the storage of aeroplanes, helicopters or space-craft.
College or university dormitory for shared living of its students.
A hardened military building.
A silo is a building for storing bulk materials.
A train station building
A building constructed to house a college.
Using this tag is discouraged, use key:demolished:building or tag:building=ruins or delete object instead.
A building constructed as a stable for horses
A small but tall building constructed to comprise a transformer and connect to an overhead power line.
A building related to the public transportation.
A cylindrical concrete structure holding liquid manure.
A building for housing cows.
A building that was built as a temple
A building built to house government offices.
A building constructed to house fire fighting equipment.
A building for raising domestic pigs.
A building designed for toilets.
Structure purpose-built for parking cars.
A grandstand at racecourse or sports ground.
A small one room retail building, with clients not entering the building.
A building that was built as a sports centre
A boat (re)constructed as a floating home, staying at a single permanent location.
A house raised on piles over the surface of the soil or a body of water.
A building providing facilities for users of sports grounds
A building built as a supermarket
A stone hut with a conical roof, built without mortar
A container used as a building.
A building that was built as a sports hall
A building mainly consisting of sheets of fabric or similar
A building which was built as stadium.
A building constructed as a digester, a bioreactor for the production of biogas from biomass.
Conservatory - a building or room having glass or tarpaulin roofing and walls used as an indoor garden or a sunroom (winter garden).
A building that was built as a religious building.
A building used as a bridge.
Using this tag is discouraged, use key:building + tag:abandoned=yes instead.
A small building constructed to house guard(s).
A small, usually wooden, and often brightly coloured cabin or shelter above the high tide mark on popular bathing beaches.
A wayside shrine that meets the criteria of a building.
A tower which is a building.
A building that was built as a shrine
An unspecific building constructed for military purposes.
A building constructed as a factory.
A building that was built as a presbytery (where priests live and work).

natural.description: A single tree.
Any inland body of water, from natural such as a lake or pond to artificial like a moat or canal.
Tree-covered area (a 'forest' or 'wood')
Uncultivated land covered with shrubs, bushes or stunted trees.
A natural area subject to inundation or with waterlogged ground
An area where the vegetation is dominated by grasses and other herbaceous (non-woody) plants.
A line of trees.
The line between sea and land indicating mean high water (springs): the water lies on the right side of the way.
An area with sparse or no vegetation, so that the bedrock becomes visible
The top (summit) of a hill or mountain.
A vertical or almost vertical natural drop in terrain, usually with a bare rock surface. The bottom of the cliff is on the right side of the way.
An area covered by sand with no or very little vegetation.
A dwarf-shrub habitat, characterised by open, low growing woody vegetation, often dominated by plants of the Ericaceae.
Unconsolidated angular stones formed by rockfall and weathering from adjacent rock faces.
A small to medium-sized single shrub, usually less than 6 meters tall.
A notable rock or group of rocks attached to the underlying bedrock
Landform along a body of water which consists of sand, shingle or other loose material.
A mountain landform with a continuous elevated crest or linear hill
A place where ground water flows naturally from the ground
A permanent body of ice formed naturally from snow that is moving under its own weight.
A feature (rock, sandbar, coral, etc) lying permanently beneath the surface of the water.
Named area of water mostly surrounded by land but with level connection to the ocean or a lake.
An accumulation of rounded rock fragments on a beach or riverbed.
A single notable freestanding rock, which may differ from the composition of the terrain it lies in.
An area of woody shrubbery that is actively maintained or pruned by humans. A slightly wilder look is also possible.
The lowest point along a ridge or between two mountain tops.
An entrance to a cave: a natural underground space large enough for a human to enter
Using this tag is discouraged, use multipolygon relation for islands in lakes and rivers or tag:natural=coastline and tag:place=island for islands in the sea instead.
A hill is a landform that is elevated above the surrounding terrain, but is smaller than a mountain.
A natural depression flanked by ridges or ranges of mountains or hills
A piece of elevated land sticking out into the sea or large lake.
A natural depression or hole in the surface topography.
A large crack in a glacier
Habitat above tree line covered with grass, dwarf shrubs and mosses.
Area covered with mud: water saturated fine grained soil without significant plant growth.
Large erosion gully or steep earth bank.
Small scale cut in relief created by water erosion.
An opening exposed on the earth's surface where volcanic material is emitted.
A base remaining from a cut down or broken tree.
Area, typically covered by grass.
A narrow area of water surrounded by land on two sides and by water on two other sides.
A bird's nest.
A thin, almost knife-like, ridge of rock which is typically formed when two glaciers erode parallel U-shaped valleys
A mountain range, a series of high ridges and mountain peaks ranged in a line and connected by high ground.
A spring of geothermally heated groundwater
An area of the water floor which nears the water surface and is exposed at low tide or when a river/lake is not full of water.
Tree group.
A termite mound is the aboveground part of a termite nest.
A hill of sand formed by wind, covered with no or very little vegetation
Debris fields from large-scale down-slope earth movements.
A piece of land projecting into water from a larger land mass, nearly surrounded by water
Treeless cold climate habitat with open, low growing sedges, grasses, mosses and lichens.
A spring characterized by intermittent discharge of water ejected turbulently and accompanied by steam
An area covered by boulder- or block-sized rocks.
A narrow valley with steep, rocky walls
A plant.
A barren area of land or desolate terrain, especially one with little water or vegetation.
A rock arch naturally formed by erosion, with an opening underneath.
An anthill is the aboveground part of an ant nest.
See natural=grassland instead. An area of natural meadow
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:natural=water + tag:water=river + tag:intermittent=yes (if often water) or tag:natural=shingle / tag:natural=sand (if almost never water) instead.
A flat highland area
Don't use, see wikipage
A fumarole is an opening in a planet's crust, which emits steam and gases
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:natural=sinkhole or tag:historic=bomb_crater instead.
A ring-shaped coral reef ithat encircles a lagoon partially or completely, and may include small islands.
A depression in the surface topography
Area where a notable flower species grows naturally

landuse.description: Area of farmland used mainly for tillage (annual crops).
A portion of land predominantly used for residential purposes.
A smaller area of grass, usually mown and managed.
Forest or woodland, sometimes considered to be restricted to managed woodlands or tree plantations.
An area of meadow or pasture: land primarily vegetated by grass and other non-woody plants, mainly used for hay or grazing.
Used to mark intentional planting of trees or shrubs maintained for food production
Area of land with farm buildings (farmhouse, sheds, stables, barns, etc.).
An area with predominantly workshops, factories or warehouses.
Used to tag vineyards, a piece of land where grapes are grown.
A place where people, or sometimes animals are buried that isn't part of a place of worship
A commercial zone, predominantly offices or services.
allotment gardens with multiple land parcels assigned to individuals or families for gardening.
An area that encloses predominantly shops.
An area of land artificially graded to hold water.
An area being built on.
An area of land used for surface extraction (open-pit mining).
An artificial lake which may be used to store water.
An open green space for general recreation, which often includes formal or informal pitches, nets and so on. Often municipally owned, sometimes part of colleges / companies or commercially operated.
Land which was developed which is no longer in use.
An area used for religious purposes.
Land area used for growing plants in greenhouses.
An area designated for flowers.
A village green is a distinctive area of grassy public land in a village centre. Not a generic tag for urban greenery.
An area occupied by multiple private garage buildings.
Area used for military purposes.
An area of land dedicated to train operation or support, including areas around tracks, rail corridors, yards, sidings, station complexes, and ancillary man-made objects along the tracks.
An area on land or water that is used to farm aquatic organisms.
Undeveloped land scheduled to turn into a construction site
An area where some or all trees have been cut down.
Represents land that is used solely for plant nurseries, which grow live plants.
A site for permanent or long term storage of waste materials.
An area predominately used for educational purposes/facilities.
A land used for a highway, including all auxiliary areas like associated footways and verges, ditches, etc.
A plot for static caravans.
A place where sea water is evaporated to extract its salt
An area covered in unspecified or various types of decorative vegetation. Consider using a more specific tag instead
An area of land that is used to keep animals
Unclear meaning, see instead landuse=orchard, landuse=plant_nursery, landuse=forest and landuse=farmland.
Usually a pedestrian refuge in the middle of highways linked by crossings.
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:landuse=farmyard or tag:landuse=farmland instead.
Pointless tag adding no value, never use it
An area dedicated to winter sports (e.g. skiing)
An area of farmland where the surface and shape of the ground is suitable for growing rice.
A place where beehives of honey bees are kept.
The harbour land, consisting of queys, wharfs, piers, warehouses, storage areas, stockpiles, service roads, railway tracks, and much more. Often behind a fence with its own access control.
A restricted area around a public water supply in order to ensure clean water.
Land used for institutional purposes. May include buildings for the government, associations or social facilities and their associated infrastructure like car parks, service roads, yards etc.
An area used as a depot for trains, buses, trams, containers or other objects.
Area surrounding a church or chapel — Deprecated: consider tag:landuse=religious instead.
An area of cultivated decorative shrubs or bushes
An area used for civic / governmental / public institutional administration buildings.
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:landuse=farmland, tag:landuse=meadow or tag:landuse=orchard instead.
An area of land used for healthcare purposes.
An excavation created by the removal of peat
A site where the fair takes place.
Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:landuse=farmyard or tag:landuse=meadow instead.
An area used for forestry activity.

leisure.description: An area designed for practising a particular sport, normally designated with appropriate markings.
A swimming pool (water area only)
A place where flowers and other plants are grown in a decorative and structured manner or for scientific purposes.
A park, usually in an urban (municipal) setting, created for recreation and relaxation.
A playground: an area designed for children to play.
A table with benches for food and rest

place.description: A smaller rural community, typically with fewer than 100-200 inhabitants, and little infrastructure.
A named place that has no population.
A smaller distinct settlement, smaller than a town with few facilities available with people traveling to nearby towns to access these.
The smallest kind of settlement (1-2 households).
A very small island.
A neighbourhood is a smaller named, geographically localised place within a suburb of a larger city or within a town or village
A named plot is a tract or parcel of land owned or meant to be owned by some owner.
An individually named farm.
A part of a town or city with a well-known name and often a distinct identity.
A quarter is a named, geographically localised place within a suburb of a larger city or within a town, which is bigger than a neighbourhood.
An important urban centre, between a village and a city in size.
Any piece of land that is completely surrounded by water and isolated from other significant landmasses.
A town or village square: a (typically) paved open space, generally of architectural significance, which is surrounded by buildings in a built-up area such as a city, town or village.
A named city block, usually surrounded by streets.
A separate settlement, which is located outside an officially inhabited locality and has its own addressing
A municipality - single urban administrative division having corporate status.
The largest urban settlement or settlements within the territory.
A county - a geographical region of a country.
Used both as a broad tag for geographic or historical areas with no clear boundary and for distinct administration areas (with specific boundaries) in some countries.
A district – a type of administrative division that, in some countries, is managed by local government.
A named group or chain of closely related islands and islets.
A large sub-national political/administrative area.
A subdistrict - a subdivision of a district used for administrative or other purposes.
A part in a larger city grouped into administrative unit.
A subdivision of a country similar to a state.
A nation state or other high-level national political/administrative area.
A large body of salt water part of, or connected to, an ocean.
A land area that forms an artificial hydrological entity enclosed by embankments and usually is under sea level.
Kenyan administrative division.
One of the seven continents: Africa, Antarctica, Asia, Europe, North America, Oceania, South America.
